'''Daniel Willis Bump''' (born 1952) is a mathematician who is a professor at [[Stanford University]]. He is a fellow of the [[American Mathematical Society]] since 2015, for "contributions to [[number theory]], [[representation theory]], [[combinatorics]], and [[random matrix theory]], as well as mathematical exposition".<ref name="ams">{{cite web|url=http://www.ams.org/profession/fellows-list |title=List of Fellows of the American Mathematical Society|publisher=ams.org|accessdate=2016-05-11}}</ref>
He obtained his Ph.D. from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1982 under the supervision of [[Walter Lewis Baily, Jr.]]<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=36902|title=Daniel Willis Bump}}</ref> Among his students is president of the [[National Association of Mathematicians]] [[Edray Goins]].
